## Project Structure
- before implementing features identify the framework or library and its version from package manifests
- record the resolved Context7 library id alongside the feature or in a note to ensure consistent lookups

## Code Style
- when citing external APIs prefer the exact signatures and option names from the latest docs retrieved via Context7
- prefer TypeScript examples when both TypeScript and JavaScript variants exist in docs

## Usage
- always consult Context7 first when you need documentation or best practices for any framework or library in this repository
- resolve the library id once then fetch its latest docs
- example

```javascript
// resolve the canonical library id
mcp__context7__resolve_library_id({ libraryName: "react" });

// fetch latest docs for the id returned by resolve
mcp__context7__get_library_docs({ context7CompatibleLibraryID: "/facebook/react" });
```

## Important operational rules
- prefer the latest stable version of the library documentation over archived or legacy pages
- when versions in the repo lag behind latest stable note breaking changes but follow the repo version unless upgrading is in scope
- re check docs after dependency updates and before major refactors